<h1 class="hero-h">How to Use Claude as a CEO <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">The CEO workflows that actually compound.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">CEOs of $5M-$50M B2B companies have unique time constraints and unique leverage points. Claude can compress some of the most expensive of those — board prep, exec memo writing, decision synthesis — if used systematically. Here's the daily workflow.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Top CEO Claude workflows: morning briefing synthesis, exec memo drafting, board prep, decision frameworks, hiring loop debriefs, and strategic POV development. Set up 4-5 focused Projects; use them daily. Saves 6-10 hours/week of context-switching and writing time.</p></div>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">The 5 CEO Projects to set up</h2><h3 class="h3">1. Morning briefing Project</h3><p class="body">Knowledge: company KPI structure, key priorities, board concerns. Daily use: paste in overnight emails, Slack DMs to review, calendar for the day. Get a 5-bullet brief of what matters.</p><h3 class="h3">2. Board prep Project</h3><p class="body">Knowledge: past board decks, KPI structure, each board member's interests. Quarterly use: dump in quarter's results; get structured deck draft + likely Q&amp;A.</p><h3 class="h3">3. Exec memo Project</h3><p class="body">Knowledge: 5-10 past strong exec memos in your voice. Use: draft any memo to the team. Edit heavily; output should sound like you.</p><h3 class="h3">4. Hiring loop Project</h3><p class="body">Knowledge: role scorecards, interview questions, your hiring philosophy. Use: synthesize interviewer feedback into a recommendation; draft offers; draft reject letters.</p><h3 class="h3">5. Strategic POV Project</h3><p class="body">Knowledge: company strategy, competitive landscape, your past writing. Use: develop POV on emerging issues; draft op-eds and LinkedIn posts; prepare for press interviews.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Daily workflow</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Morning (15 min):</strong> Brief Project pulls together overnight context. Plan day with priority Q&amp;A.</li><li><strong>Between meetings (5-10 min each):</strong> Quick syntheses of conversations, drafted follow-ups.</li><li><strong>End of day (20 min):</strong> Synthesize day's decisions, draft any communications, prep for tomorrow.</li><li><strong>Weekly (60-90 min):</strong> Strategic thinking session — use Claude as a sparring partner on hard decisions, paste in relevant context, get challenged.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Where to be cautious</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Don't let AI write your team-facing communications without heavy edit.</strong> Voice matters; team detects fakery.</li><li><strong>Don't use AI for sensitive personnel decisions (firing, comp).</strong> Both judgment and confidentiality stakes are too high.</li><li><strong>Don't paste confidential M&amp;A or board materials into anything but enterprise-tier with explicit no-training.</strong></li><li><strong>Don't outsource the hardest thinking.</strong> AI accelerates the easy parts of CEO work; the hardest parts remain yours.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Specific high-leverage prompts</h2><h3 class="h3">Decision framework prompt</h3><p class="body"><em>"Help me think through [decision]. Steelman the case for option A. Steelman the case for option B. What information am I missing? What would change my mind? What is the reversible/irreversible analysis?"</em></p><h3 class="h3">Steelman objection prompt</h3><p class="body"><em>"I am about to ship [communication/decision]. Pretend you are [our toughest board member / our most skeptical exec / our most savvy competitor]. What would you push back on?"</em></p><h3 class="h3">POV development prompt</h3><p class="body"><em>"I have been thinking about [emerging topic]. Here are my raw thoughts: [dump]. Help me develop this into a distinctive POV that I could articulate publicly. Where is my thinking soft? What do I need to clarify?"</em></p></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How much CEO time does this save?</h3><p class="faq-qa">6-10 hours/week typical for CEOs who use AI daily. Compounds with team adoption.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I use Claude or ChatGPT as CEO?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Either. Claude tends to be stronger for editorial work and calibration; ChatGPT for breadth and tool ecosystem. Pick one; train deeply.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I let my EA use my Claude account?</h3><p class="faq-qa">No. Get them their own seat. Boundaries on what each person uses Claude for matter.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Will my board be impressed or concerned that I use AI?</h3><p class="faq-qa">In 2026, expected. Most boards now ask whether the company uses AI internally. "Yes, here is how" is the right answer.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I use Claude on my phone?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Mobile Claude is useful for quick capture and quick lookups. Save heavy work for desktop.</p></div>
</div></section>

